node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.text: Photos by @christianpondella / A ski mountaineering adventure in the high Andes with @giuliamonego and @american_dave. Based in and around La Paz, Bolivia, we had our sights set to ski on Illimani and Huayna Potosí, the 6,000-meter (19,685-foot) peaks that dominate the views from La Paz.

node.text: Photo by @erinhogue / The moment just after the sun dips and alpine glow is in full force. The process of getting to this moment was anything but casual. It was a week of stressfully analyzing the weather, on top of a logistical nightmare of organizing riders, filmers, other crews, insurance, and the resort, all with thousands of dollars on the line. It culminated in an evening of milky skies threatening to ruin the entire production, rendering everyone’s hard work meaningless. Luckily, the British Columbian skies were on our side and provided one of the most gorgeous sunsets I've ever seen. @sebbedebuck

node.text: Photo by @andy_best / I moved to Oregon for the first time just after my 19th birthday in 2004. I was off to film school in Portland at the start of the digital revolution. I packed my little ‘94 Ford Escort up with a few belongings, laundry basket full of clothes, computer, guitar, skateboards, the essentials. Along with my Panasonic 3CCD chipped video camera and my Nikon D40X ready to capture the new world. I worked at a grocery store 40 hours a week while taking 16 credits, all the while working part time at an internship. This all meant I didn't sleep one night each week to clock in all these hours to survive and graduate with a job. I'm asked often how to get into this industry; my answer is always: grind. For more of my journey, please visit @andy_best.

node.text: Photo by @paulzizkaphoto / Spending time in the presence of mighty Mount Assiniboine is always special. Look closely and you'll see @trixie_ on the summit ridge of Mount Gloria providing a sense of scale. This image shows a less common perspective of Mount Assiniboine. The peak is more frequently photographed from the shores of Lake Magog or from The Nub, places that best showcase Assiniboine's pyramidal shape and prominence.

node.text: Photos by @michaelclarkphoto / Kaz Sheekey swooping through a blazing fire during the 2021 Highlight Pro Skydiving team training camp at Skydive Arizona in Eloy, Arizona. While this image has an apocalyptic feel, the skydivers flew through the flames at 60 mph (96 kph) and barely even felt the heat. I was standing about 20 meters (66 feet) away and off to the side so I didn't get hit by them as they came through the wall of fire. #skydiving #skydiver #walloffire #swooping

node.text: Photo by @andy_best / The future of our planet witnessing the now fifth season, fire season. There IS hope in all our young people. They are strong, resilient, beautiful, and love this wonderful world. It takes guidance and patience, but it’s an effort that is required. My daughter pictured here has lived on the road most of her life and will be a force. It's amazing to watch them grow and develop a much-needed love for everyone and everything out here.
